qas.question: When the Latin alphabet was introduced to Old English, what letter was the same as v?
Along with k and z, what Latin letter was not used in Old English?
What is the term for the letter þ?
What number was the Tironian note visually similar to?
What was the term for the letter ƿ?
What was originally used to mark long vowels?

plausible_answers.text: as digraphs, representing a single sound.

qas.question: What were most letter pairs used for?

context: The Latin alphabet of the time still lacked the letters ⟨j⟩ and ⟨w⟩, and there was no ⟨v⟩ as distinct from ⟨<a0_0>u<a0_0/>⟩; moreover native Old English spellings did not use ⟨k⟩, ⟨<a1_0>q<a1_0/>⟩ or ⟨z⟩. The remaining 20 Latin letters were supplemented by four more: ⟨æ⟩ (æsc, modern ash) and ⟨ð⟩ (ðæt, now called eth or edh), which were modified Latin letters, and <a2_0>thorn<a2_0/> ⟨þ⟩ and <a4_0>wynn<a4_0/> ⟨<a3_0>ƿ<a3_0/>⟩, which are borrowings from the futhorc. A few letter pairs were used <b6_0>as digraphs, representing a single sound.<b6_0/> Also used was the Tironian note ⟨⁊⟩ (a character similar to the digit 7) for the conjunction and, and a thorn with a crossbar through the ascender for the pronoun þæt. <b5_0>Macrons<b5_0/> over vowels were originally used not to mark long vowels (as in modern editions), but to indicate stress, or as abbreviations for a following m or n.
